                <p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><b><span class="spnMessageText"><a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=782" title="View Etadanik Mistmorgue's Profile" onMouseOver="(window.status='View Etadanik Mistmorgue\'s Profile'); return true" onMouseOut="(window.status=''); return true">Etadanik Mistmorgue</a></span></b></font><br />
                <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"><small>Spectre</small></font><br />
                </p>
                <p>
                <td bgcolor="#333366" height="100%" width="100%" colspan="2" valign="top"><a name="104126"></a>
                  <table width="100%" height="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                    <tr>
                      <td colspan="2" valign="top">
                      <img src="images/icon_mi_1.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="" title="" hspace="3" /><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/08/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 04:47:50 AM</font>
                      &nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=782"><img src="images/icon_profile.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Show Profile" title="Show Profile" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=104126&TOPIC_ID=11893&FORUM_ID=2"><img src="images/icon_reply_topic.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Reply with Quote" title="Reply with Quote" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      <hr noshade size="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="Verdana" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">You should find some that can be purchased, some quested, some dropped. We’ll probably use all three methods. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />/cynic-mode on<br /><br />Hmph.  This is exactly what they did, Daedrea. Dark Plague can be purchased - and so can other spells, from the bazaar that is.  "Some" quested - yeah, the spell turn-ins ARE quests, so pretty much all the parchment spells are "quested", and let's not forget the Imbue spells, which are quested.  And dropped - well, you need to get drops from mobs in order to do the quests, so in a twisted way the spells are also "dropped."<br /><br />So in essence, VI did exactly what they said they would - except, it's a twisted, demented version that you'd honestly not expect from reading those words.<br /><br />/cynic-mode off<br /><br />Anyways, that aside, my problem with PoP is muc more deeply rooted than yours is.  I feel the idea of forcing you to work for ALL your spells is not a good development in EQ.  I like the idea of working for *some* spells - powerful ones like Grangrenous Touch and Funeral Pyre, though I would more if they were quested/researched than drop off of uber mobs.  I even like the idea of Ancient spells that most people won't see but of which serves as a balance between uber casters and uber melees.  Those things are alright with me because they reward those who pursue after them, and a game needs that in order to remain appealing.<br /><br />But they must be done in an existing context of balance.  They should be extensions of balance rather than a fulfillment of it.  The game must be playable and balanced without these rare, powerful spells.  They should be additions, not fundamentals, of game design.  <br /><br />Currently this is not true in PoP.<br /><br />Observe the typical player.  He can make level 65 in a month or less in PoP, and indeed many have done so.  But what then? What can he do, if he was not in a powerful guild, to obtain the spectral parchments and runes in order to advance his character? Currently, not alot.  He can hope for rare drops in tier 2/3 zones for his level 63-64 spells, but runes? He'd not see them for months, if not years.  The trickling down of spells that many mention will happen eventually will not happen in PoP for a long time to come, people.  It will happen so late, in fact, that I think many people will get discouraged and give the finger to Verant before they'll obtain their first bazaar-bought level 65 spell.  Why must this be? Because VI wants players to go on playing longer? There are better ways to ensure that, methinks. <br /><br />The joy of playing a caster comes in casting spells and getting new spells as we level.  VI needs to realize this and stop denying casters their spells.  This game is simply no longer fun when you go night after night hoping that you'd see a rare drop off of some mob and win the random roll that'll give it to you, and then hope that the random number generator will give you a spell you had hoped for - that ultimately only completes your balance, rather than add to it. <br /><br />The important thing to realize is that this is not like Funeral Pyre at all, where you felt a rush of excitement and pride at having attained the spell, knowing yourself to be then "above" the balance.  There is no sense of achievement in getting LoZ, ToM, or Neurotoxin.  Every necro knows that at level 61 you need those spells in order to be balanced with the mobs you'd have to fight at those levels.  At level 65, you need Blood of Thule, the 65 pet, etc. in order to be balanced against the enemies you'd face at those levels.  This principle is further emphasized with the new trivial system that makes mobs that you were fighting for great exp at 60 quickly go lite-blue or even green as you leveled.  This was a sign to us that we should be somehow above these mobs.  Yet how can we be, if most of our spells are rare drops that we won't see for a long time to come?<br /><br />That's the reality of it: the breaking of the mentality that VI has maintained all these years about caster balance.  We were balanced in the past because we always had a set of spells that were given to us either freely (with some minor pp costs) or with very little effort.  That was the "standard" gift of advancement and what you got out of leveling.  The rest were additions you could do without, but felt the urge to work towards because you want to better yourself past mediocrity.  This urge, which lead players to raid and challenge themselves, was a great vitalizing force for the game.  No longer.  Now raiding is REQUIRED for advancement.  No raiding for you? No advancement past the eary 60's.  It is no longer your choice whether to raid and be uber, or simply to lay back and advance slowly.  It is now a requirement that you do the former - and thus, it feels like work, and thus, it's not fun.<br /><br />There comes a point, and it's different for everyone, when a person just has to look at EQ and ask themselves whether they're playing a game anymore.  Now, in PoP, I think that point is approaching for alot of us.<br /><br /><br />Etadanik the Redeemed</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
